<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>sparsifolium</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>glandulosa</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>glauca</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>pungens</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>crassifolius</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cuneatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>greggii</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>megacarpus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>spinosus</i>, <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>montanus</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>linearifolia</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Garrya</i> <i>veatchii</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Heteromeles</i> <i>arbutifolia</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>basilaris</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>berberidifolia</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>cornelius</i>-<i>mulleri</i>, <i>Rhamnus</i> <i>ilicifolia</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i> and <i>Yucca</i> <i>schidigera</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 5 m; canopy is open to
intermittent. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Adenostoma sparsifolium</i> > 60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Gordon and White 1994, Borchert et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li>Both <i>Adenostoma sparsifolium</i> and <i>A. fasciculatum</i> are 30-60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Gordon and White 1994). Other species such as <i>Ceanothus crassifolius</i> may be similar cover (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Variable topography and slopes. Soils are shallow to deep and derived from alluvial or bedrock, often sandy loams and may be rocky.  </div>
</div>

        
