<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Adenostoma sparsifolium </i>is an evergreen, sclerophyllous shrub that can grow to 6 m in height. Older plants have continuous shedding of bark. Seeds disperse during the summer near the parent plant. Dormant seeds accumulate in a soil bank and are not subject to heavy predation. Shrubs rejuvenate their crowns by continually producing new sprouts from a lignotuber (Howard 1993a). <br/>
<br/>
Stands dominated by <i>A. sparsifolium </i>are relatively uncommon as compared to mixed ones with <i>A. fasciculatum</i>. Marion (1943) found monotypic stands of <i>A. sparsifolium </i>in just 3% of its distribution. However both variants, originally defined as separate series (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 1995), are now considered in this single alliance description where <i>A. sparsifolium </i>is either co-dominant to strongly dominant. Stands occupy in a variety of topographic settings from dry washes and gentle toe slopes to steep ridges. Stands may occupy frequently burned areas, and some associations appear to have desert influences (Gordon and White 1994). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
