<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Stands <i>of Adenistoma sparsifolium </i>are generally more open than are those dominated by <i>A. fasciculatum, </i>but they have more standing dead fuel and deeper litter because of continuous shedding of bark and stems. The sticky leaves contain a flammable resin, so fires spread along the ground and through the shrub canopy. Heat and charcoal stimulate seed germination during the first rainy season after a fire, and plants vigorously sprout from surviving adventitious buds of the lignotuber (Howard 1993a, Marion 1943). Stands grow quickly back after fires and reach maximum canopy cover and height within approximately 25 years (Gordon and White 1994). 

For both <i>Adenostoma </i>species, heat and charcoal stimulate germination from the seed bank during the first rainy season after fire (Howard 1993a, McMurray 1990a). The surviving adventitious buds in the lignotubers sprout following fire and cutting. In a study in the Santa Monica Mountains (Barton 1995), post-fire seedling establishment and survivorship was > 10% higher for <i>A. fasciculatum </i>after three years than it was for <i>A. sparsifolium. </i>

This alliance usually responds quickly to low- to moderate-intensity fires via seed germination and abundant sprouting. Research on <i>A. fasciculatum </i>showed that high-intensity fires delayed sprouting and resulted in fewer sprouts compared to low-intensity fires. High-intensity fire decreased germination and seedling emergence since seeds tend be concentrated at or near the soil surface, rendering them vulnerable to heat-kill (Moreno and Oechel 1991, 1993). <i>A. sparsifolium </i>may overtop <i>A. fasciculatum </i>within 40 years, but cover of <i>A. fasciculatum </i>often remains unchanged (Gordon and White 1994).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
