    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ae, Aj). Stands exist in the southern Santa Lucia Mountains (Borchert et al. 2004) primarily on sandstone substrates and southerly-facing slopes.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Be-f). Stands are uncommon in the western Transverse Ranges (Borchert et al. 2004) and Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), where they occur on metamorphic, sedimentary, and volcanic substrates. Most mixed stands also have high cover of <i>Ceanothus crassifolius.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-c, Bl-m, Bo-p). Stands are in the San Jacinto and other Peninsular mountains (Gordon and White 1994, Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, Klein and Evens 2005), mostly on granitic or alluvial substrates. Stands appear to occur in the western Transverse Ranges.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
